{{Otheruses2|5G}}

'''5G''' is the name given to the next phase of mobile telecommunications standards after the current [[4G]] standards are implemented between approximately 2010 and 2012. Currently it is not a term officially used for any particular standards yet made public by telecommunication companies or organisations, as the 4G standards are still in the late [[Research and development|R&D]] stages before being implemented by products in the marketplace. Furthermore, much like the previous [[2G]] and [[3G]] standards before it, the 4G standard will most likely be improved upon before 5G arrives, with so-called '''4.5G''' technologies. 

It is expected that in terms of data streams, such a standard would have download and upload speeds in the 10 to 100 [[Gbps#Gigabit_per_second|Gbps]] range or higher. Though many other technologies would also be a part of the overall package of aims for such standards, and some of the research into possible 4G standards that were not successful may ultimately end up as possible contenders for these 5G standards. 

The likely implementation of standards under the 5G umbrella would likely be post-2015 at the earliest, although any timeframe is far from being clear at this very early stage. 

